  <!-- SECTION 3: GPU -->
  <div class=3D"section">
    <div class=3D"section-num">03 =E2=80=94 NVIDIA GPU Market</div>
    <div class=3D"section-title">The Mining-Driven Shortage &amp; Post-Cras=
h Correction</div>
    <p class=3D"section-body">
      GPU demand from cryptocurrency mining is not new =E2=80=94 it traces =
back to Bitcoin's early days in 2013, when consumer graphics cards were the=
 primary mining hardware. That changed when custom ASICs replaced GPUs for =
Bitcoin, making general-purpose cards unprofitable for BTC mining. The cycl=
e restarted with Ethereum, which was intentionally designed with an ASIC-re=
sistant mining algorithm, making GPUs the only viable mining hardware again=
. This design choice is what made the 2020=E2=80=932022 shortage so severe:=
 every GPU sold was competing between two entirely separate demand pools =
=E2=80=94 gamers and miners =E2=80=94 with no dedicated supply chain for ei=
ther.
    </p>
    <p class=3D"section-body">
      NVIDIA's RTX 30-series launched in September 2020 at <strong>$699 MSR=
P (RTX 3080)</strong>. According to research from Jon Peddie Research, cryp=
to miners purchased an estimated <strong>25% of all GPUs produced in the fi=
rst half of 2021</strong>. With pandemic-related chip shortages shrinking s=
upply at the same timely, secondary market prices reached <strong>3x retail=
 or higher</strong> by February 2021. The feedback loop of the shortage mad=
e it worse: miners had little incentive to sell cards that were actively ge=
nerating returns, further restricting secondary market supply. When Ethereu=
m transitioned to proof-of-stake in September 2022, eliminating GPU mining =
profitability overnight, miners began liquidating their entire fleets at th=
e same timely. Combined with the RTX 40-series launch, the 30-series overco=
rrected below MSRP by early 2023 =E2=80=94 creating a clear re-entry window=
 before gaming demand stabilized prices.
    </p>

    <div class=3D"chart-card">
      <div class=3D"chart-title">RTX 3080, Secondary Market Price vs. MSRP =
(2020=E2=80=932023)</div>
      <div class=3D"chart-wrap"><canvas id=3D"gpuChart" width=3D"1524" heig=
ht=3D"480" style=3D"display: block; box-sizing: border-box; height: 240px; =
width: 762px;"></canvas></div>
    </div>

    <div class=3D"findings">
      <div class=3D"finding" style=3D"border-color:var(--orange);">
        <div class=3D"finding-tag" style=3D"color:var(--orange);">Key Drive=
r: Dual Demand Pool</div>
        <div class=3D"finding-text">Ethereum's GPU-only mining design made =
GPUs the only viable mining hardware, putting gamers and miners in direct c=
ompetition for the same supply. At peak ETH prices, a single RTX 3080 could=
 generate $8=E2=80=9312/day in mining revenue, making miners unwilling to s=
ell even at 3x retail markup.</div>
      </div>
      <div class=3D"finding" style=3D"border-color:var(--blue);">
        <div class=3D"finding-tag" style=3D"color:var(--blue);">Signal: Pos=
t-Merge Liquidation Window</div>
        <div class=3D"finding-text">Ethereum's shift to proof-of-stake in S=
eptember 2022 made GPU mining instantly unprofitable. The resulting mass li=
quidation of mining fleets pushed 30-series prices 10=E2=80=9320% below MSR=
P by Q1 2023, a short-term pricing gap before organic gaming demand restore=
d normal pricing.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- SECTION 4: PS5 -->
  <div class=3D"section">
    <div class=3D"section-num">04 =E2=80=94 PlayStation 5</div>
    <div class=3D"section-title">Supply Constraints, Remote Demand &amp; th=
e Restock Race</div>
    <p class=3D"section-body">
      The PlayStation 5 launched in November 2020 at <strong>$499 MSRP</str=
ong> into one of the worst supply environments in consumer electronics hist=
ory. Sony's semiconductor supply was constrained by the same global chip sh=
ortage affecting GPU manufacturers, while demand was amplified by locked-do=
wn consumers with stimulus money and nowhere to spend it. Units retailed fo=
r <strong>$800=E2=80=931,200</strong> on secondary markets through 2021=E2=
=80=932022. Restocks were sporadic, unpredictable, and sold out within minu=
tes, making automated monitoring and alert systems essential to capturing i=
nventory at retail price before bots cleared stock.
    </p>

    <div class=3D"chart-card">
      <div class=3D"chart-title">PlayStation 5, Secondary Market Price vs. =
MSRP (2021=E2=80=932023)</div>
      <div class=3D"chart-wrap"><canvas id=3D"ps5Chart" width=3D"1524" heig=
ht=3D"480" style=3D"display: block; box-sizing: border-box; height: 240px; =
width: 762px;"></canvas></div>
    </div>

    <div class=3D"findings">
      <div class=3D"finding" style=3D"border-color:var(--purple);">
        <div class=3D"finding-tag" style=3D"color:var(--purple);">Methodolo=
gy: Restock Monitoring</div>
        <div class=3D"finding-text">PS5 restocks at major retailers (Best B=
uy, Target, Walmart) followed predictable patterns. Monitoring inventory en=
dpoints and social signals allowed for advance positioning before public an=
nouncements.</div>
      </div>
      <div class=3D"finding" style=3D"border-color:var(--green);">
        <div class=3D"finding-tag" style=3D"color:var(--green);">Signal: Ma=
rgin Compression (2023)</div>
        <div class=3D"finding-text">By mid-2023, Sony had resolved the bulk=
 of its supply constraints. Secondary margins compressed from 60=E2=80=9380=
% premium to 5=E2=80=9310%, signaling a category exit point for resale-focu=
sed inventory.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- SECTION 5: COLLECTIBLES -->
  <div class=3D"section">
    <div class=3D"section-num">05 =E2=80=94 PSA-Graded Collectibles</div>
    <div class=3D"section-title">Stimulus-Fueled Speculation &amp; the Mark=
et Split</div>
    <p class=3D"section-body">
      The collectibles market followed the same stimulus-driven pattern as =
electronics. Influencer coverage of Pok=C3=A9mon cards in early 2021, combi=
ned with millions of people at home with extra cash and no live entertainme=
nt, triggered a speculative wave that sent PSA-graded card prices up <stron=
g>200=E2=80=93400%</strong> from pre-pandemic levels. By 2023, the broad ma=
rket had corrected 40=E2=80=9360% as speculators exited. However, the corre=
ction was not uniform: high-grade cards (PSA 9/10) in low-population, iconi=
c sets retained value far better than bulk mid-grade inventory, showing tha=
t the market had matured and only quality inventory held its value.
    </p>

    <div class=3D"chart-card">
      <div class=3D"chart-title">PSA Collectibles Market, High-Grade vs. Br=
oad Market Index (2020=E2=80=932023, Base: 100)</div>
      <div class=3D"chart-wrap"><canvas id=3D"psaChart" width=3D"1524" heig=
ht=3D"480" style=3D"display: block; box-sizing: border-box; height: 240px; =
width: 762px;"></canvas></div>
    </div>

    <div class=3D"findings">
      <div class=3D"finding" style=3D"border-color:var(--green);">
        <div class=3D"finding-tag" style=3D"color:var(--green);">Insight: Q=
uality Holds Value</div>
        <div class=3D"finding-text">PSA 10 cards in low-pop sets declined o=
nly 10=E2=80=9315% from peak, while the broad market fell 50%+. Concentrati=
on in high-grade assets was the correct strategy entering the correction.</=
div>
      </div>
      <div class=3D"finding" style=3D"border-color:var(--orange);">
        <div class=3D"finding-tag" style=3D"color:var(--orange);">Risk: Bul=
k Inventory</div>
        <div class=3D"finding-text">Speculative buyers who held mid-grade c=
ommon-set cards faced severe liquidity issues as the market cooled. Demand =
monitoring via sell-through data flagged this deterioration early.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- RECOMMENDATION -->
  <div class=3D"section">
    <div class=3D"section-num">06 =E2=80=94 Strategic Takeaways</div>
    <div class=3D"section-title">What the Data Indicated for H1 2023</div>
    <div class=3D"rec">
      <div class=3D"rec-label">Analyst Conclusion</div>
      <div class=3D"rec-title">Macro Timing + Real-Time Monitoring =3D Sour=
cing Edge</div>
      <p class=3D"rec-body">
        The core insight across all three categories was that <strong>macro=
 signals and on-the-ground monitoring worked together</strong>, neither alo=
ne was sufficient. CPI and crypto data explained why pricing was where it w=
as; social monitoring, search trends, and restock alerts determined when an=
d where to act.<br><br>
        <strong>GPUs:</strong> The post-mining correction created a below-M=
SRP acquisition window. Gaming demand remained structurally intact, making =
this a clear buy signal for Q1 2023 with an expected recovery to 10=E2=80=
=9315% above MSRP within 60=E2=80=9390 days.<br><br>
        <strong>PS5:</strong> Supply normalization by mid-2023 shrank secon=
dary margins to near zero. The category required exit or a pivot toward bun=
dle configurations that maintained perceived value above commodity pricing.=
<br><br>
        <strong>Collectibles:</strong> Market maturation favored quality co=
ncentration. Monitoring sell-through velocity on PSA 10 low-pop cards showe=
d resilience while bulk inventory flagged as a liquidation priority.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class=3D"report-footer">
    <div>
